03493nam a22005895i 9780804797559DE-B159720200723103303.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||200723t20202016cau    fo  d z      eng d  a97808047975597 a10.1515/97808047975592doi  a(DE-B1597)564805  a(OCoLC)1178770037  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  acaucUS-CA 4aPL845.B4bZ59 2017 7aHIS0210002bisacsh04a895.6352231 aCalichman, Richard, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aBeyond Nation :bTime, Writing, and Community in the Work of Abe Kōbō /cRichard Calichman. 1aStanford, CA : bStanford University Press, c[2020] 4c©2016  a1 online resource (288 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tCONTENTS -- tACKNOWLEDGMENTS -- tINTRODUCTION -- tONE. MARKINGS IN THE SAND -- tTWO. THE TIME OF DISTURBANCE -- tTHREE. THE LURE OF COMMUNITY IN TANIN NO KAO -- tFOUR. INTERVENTIONS -- tEPILOGUE -- tNOTES -- tBIBLIOGRAPHY -- tINDEX 0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn the work of writer Abe Kōbō (1924-1993), characters are alienated both from themselves and from one another. Through close readings of Abe's work, Richard Calichman reveals how time and writing have the ability to unground identity. Over time, attempts to create unity of self cause alienation, despite government attempts to convince people to form communities (and nations) to recapture a sense of wholeness. Art, then, must resist the nation-state and expose its false ideologies. Calichman argues that Abe's attack on the concept of national affiliation has been neglected through his inscription as a writer of Japanese literature. At the same time, the institution of Japan Studies works to tighten the bond between nation-state and individual subject. Through Abe's essays and short stories, he shows how the formation of community is constantly displaced by the notions of time and writing. Beyond Nation thus analyzes the elements of Orientalism, culturalism, and racism that often underlie the appeal to collective Japanese identity.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 23. Jul 2020) 0aIdentity (Psychology) in literature. 4aAbe Kōbō. 4aJapanese literature. 4acommunity. 4adeconstruction. 4anationalism. 4aracism. 4atime. 4awriting. 7aHISTORY / Asia / Japan.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertSUP Complete eBook-Package 2016z978311070397940uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780804797559zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780804797559423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780804797559.jpg  a978-3-11-070397-9  SUP Complete eBook-Package 2016b2016  aGBV-deGruyter-alles